did.unittitle: Workforce Development Institute Unseenamerica NYS Photographs
did.abstract: Unseenamerica NYS is a photography and writing workshop class offered to working men and women across New York by the Workforce Development Institute.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: 12 boxes of photographs, negatives, and printed material from unseen America: New York State, a project showcasing the lives and experiences of workers. Photographic prints include 10x15 black and white prints and 4x6 color and black and white photos. Box 12 contains a binder with photocopies of proofs from boxes 1-5. Photographs were taken beween 2004 and 2010 in many cities and towns in upstate New York, including Albany, Binghamton, Buffalo, Gloversville, Poughkeepsie, Purchase, and Utica. A project collaboration between the Workforce Development Institute, Bread & Roses, and SEIU/1199.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Three sets of posters from Bread & Roses and Workforce Development Institute promoting specific labor unions were separated and added to the Tamiment/Wagner Poster collection.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Workforce Development Institute (WDI) is a New York State nonprofit that provides programs in workforce, economic, and community development in order to improve the lives of working families around the State. The WDI Art of Labor program provides photography, writing, and art workshops to capture stories of workers across New York. Unseenamerica NYS is a 10-12 week photography and writing workshop class offered to working men and women across New York.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Copyright (or related rights to publicity and privacy) for materials in this collection, created by the Workforce Development Institute was not transferred to New York University. Permission to use materials must be secured from the copyright holder.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Donated by the Workforce Development Institute, under an agreement with Ed Murphy (executive director), 2011. The accession number associated with this gift is 2011.034.

A staff member will respond to you with further information.
